Spring Cloud (Simple Form)
Spring Cloud is a toolkit in Java that makes it easy to build and manage microservices.

üî• What It Does:
Connects services ‚Üí Helps services find each other (Eureka).

Routes requests ‚Üí Manages incoming requests (API Gateway).

Shares settings ‚Üí One place to store configurations for all services.

Handles failures ‚Üí Keeps the system running smoothly even if some services fail.

üõ†Ô∏è Real-Life Example:
In a food delivery app:

Order Service ‚Üí Takes customer orders.

Payment Service ‚Üí Handles payments.

Delivery Service ‚Üí Manages delivery.

‚úÖ Spring Cloud makes sure these services:

Find each other without hardcoding IPs.

Share common settings easily.

Keep working even if one service fails.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Imagine you have a bunch of services talking to each other. If Service A calls Service B, but Service B is slow or completely down, Service A could keep waiting, causing delays or even crashing. To prevent this, you use a circuit breaker.

üî• How it works:
‚úÖ Normal state (Closed):

Service A calls Service B as usual. Everything is fine.

‚ùå Failure state (Open):

If Service B keeps failing (e.g., too many errors), the circuit breaker "trips" and stops calling Service B for a while.

Instead, it can return a default response or an error message.

üîÑ Half-open state:

After some time, the circuit breaker tries to call Service B again.

If the call succeeds, it goes back to normal (closed). If it fails, it stays open.

üí° Why use it?
Prevents cascading failures ‚Üí One failing service won't crash the entire system.

Improves resilience ‚Üí The system stays responsive by returning fallback responses.

Reduces load on failing services ‚Üí Gives them time to recover.

üõ†Ô∏è Example
If you have a payment service that depends on an inventory service:

Without a circuit breaker ‚Üí The payment service could hang or fail if the inventory service is down.

With a circuit breaker ‚Üí The payment service quickly detects the issue, returns a fallback message, and keeps running smoothly.
